hi Channel]], [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] [[destroyer]] ''Kuretake'' ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u5449\u7af9 (\u99c6\u9010\u8266)|\u5449\u7af9]]}}), [[High-speed transport|transport]] ''[[Tamatsu Maru]]'' and many other ships attacked then [[shipwrecking]] by [[United States Navy]] in [[Pacific War]] time. This area was called {{Nihongo|Cemetery of Ships|\u8239\u306e\u5e55\u5834\u306e|Fume no hakaba}} in Japan, more than 100,000 killed in action. Japanese veteran {{Nihongo|Hidetsugu Nakajima|\u4e2d\u5d8b\u79c0\u6b21|extra=died 2013}} survived for 12 days and saved in August 1944. He built \u2019\u2019Cyouonji\u2019\u2019 temple privately at his own cost in 1981 for killed fellow soldier [[memorialization]] and, 60 deceased's family, [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] and Japanese attended menorial ceremony in August 2015.<ref>[[Yomiuri Shimbun]] 2015-Aug.-3 ver. 13S page 4</ref>\n\n==== Tajikistan ====\n* [[Dushanbe]], Tajikistan office of [[United Nations Development Programme]] - Cenotaph, Yutaka Akino ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u79cb\u91ce\u8c4a|\u79cb\u91ce\u8c4a]]}}), voluntary participate from [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)]] staff, dead on duty of [[United Nations Mission of Observers in Tajikistan]].<ref>[[Shinz\u014d Abe]] floral tribute on 2015-10-24, [[Yomiuri Shimbun]] Page 4, 13S edition 2015-10-25</ref>\n\n==== Thailand ====\n\n*[[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya District|Ayutthaya]] - Japanese cemetery is in [[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya District|Ayutthaya]]\n* [[Kanchanaburi]] - {{Nihongo|Cenotaph, Kanchanaburi Memorial Monument|\u30ab\u30f3\u30c1\u30e3\u30ca\u30d6\u30ea\u30fc\u6170\u970a\u5854|Kanchanaburi ireitou}}, Japanese soldiers worked to build [[Mueang Kanchanaburi District]] [[Burma Railway]], including [[prisoner of war]] of [[Allies of World War II]] and workers from the [[Southeast Asia]] region. Built by the Japanese army railway build troops in 1944. [[Epitaph]] is in language with Japanese, English, [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]].\n\n==== Uzbekistan ====\nThere are thirteen Japanese cemeteries in Uzbekistan.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://uz.iio.org.uk/tashkent_jpn_cemetery.htm |script-title=ja:\u30bf\u30b7\u30b1\u30f3\u30c8\u306b\u7720\u308b\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6291\u7559\u8005\n |language =Japanese|trans-title = Japanese prisoners of war buried in Tashkent\n | access-date =2016-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.uz.emb-japan.go.jp/jp/relations/political/boti.html |script-title=ja:\u5728\u30a6\u30ba\u30d9\u30ad\u30b9\u30bf\u30f3\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u5927\u4f7f\u9928|date =2016-01-01|language=Japanese|trans-title=Japanese Embassy in Uzbekistan|access-date =2016-06-06}}</ref>\n\n* [[Andijan]]\n* [[Angren, Uzbekistan|Angren]]\n* [[Bekabad]]\n* [[Bukhara]]\n* [[Chirchiq]]\n* [[Fergana]]\n* [[Kokand]]\n* [[Tashkent]] \u2013 Tashkent Japanese prisoners of war in Tashkent [[Yakkasaray]] citizen cemetery {{nihongo||\u30e4\u30c3\u30ab\u30b5\u30e9\u30a4\u5e02\u6c11\u5893\u5730\u5185[[:ja:\u30bf\u30b7\u30b1\u30f3\u30c8\u6291\u7559\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730|\u30bf\u30b7\u30b1\u30f3\u30c8\u6291\u7559\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730]]|}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uz.iio.org.uk/tashkent_jpn_cemetery.htm |script-title=ja:\u30bf\u30b7\u30b1\u30f3\u30c8\u6291\u7559\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730\u3001\u30a6\u30ba\u30d9\u30ad\u30b9\u30bf\u30f3 |website=uz.iio.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uz.emb-japan.go.jp/jp/relations/political/boti.html |script-title=ja:\u5728\u30a6\u30ba\u30d9\u30ad\u30b9\u30bf\u30f3\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u5927\u4f7f\u9928 |publisher=Embassy of Japan in Uzbekistan}}</ref>\n\n==== Vietnam ====\n[[H\u1ed9i An]] - H\u1ed9i An Japanese cemetery, 30 years after many Japanese started [[foreign trade]] by [[Red seal ships]], but [[Sakoku]] began then people could not return to Japan and died there.\n\n=== Africa ===\n==== Madagascar ====\n* Two cenotaph of four Japanese [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] killed in [[Battle of Madagascar]] in [[Antsiranana]], named ''Diego-Suarez'' prior to 1975. First cenotaph for two of four Japanese constructed in 1976 by Japanese [[embassy]]. Second cenotaph of four Japanese constructed by voluntary war veteran in 1997.\n\n=== Oceania ===\n==== Australia ====\n* [[Broome, Western Australia]] \u2013 Burial of approximately 900 Japanese immigrants in the [[Meiji period]] from [[Taiji, Wakayama]].The immigrants were in Broome to dive for [[pearl]]<nowiki/>s.\n* [[Cowra]] - Cemetery of [[Cowra breakout]] Japanese. \n* [[Darwin, Northern Territory]] \u2013 Cenotaph of [[I-121-class submarine]].<ref>{{cite news\n | title =\u5b89\u500d\u5185\u95a3\u7dcf\u7406\u5927\u81e3\u306b\u3088\u308b\u8c6a\u5dde\u30c0\u30fc\u30a6\u30a3\u30f3\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u4f0a\u53f7\u7b2c124\u6f5c\u6c34\u8266\u6170\u970a\u7891\u8a2a\u554f 2-19-11-17\n | url =https://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/a_o/ocn/au/page4_004508.html \n | agency =  [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)]]\n | accessdate =2019-05-19\n | language = Japanese\n | trans_title =\n | quote =[[Prime Minister of Japan]] [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] visit cenotaph of [[I-121-class submarine]] at [[Darwin, Northern Territory]] on 2018 Nov. 17\n }}</ref>  \n* [[Thursday Island, Queensland]] \u2013 Cemetery of Japanese immigrants from the [[Meiji period]] to the end of [[World War II]]. Primary occupation was diving for pearls.\n\n==== [[Guam]] ====\n* ''South Pacific Memorial Park'', Cenotaph of South Pacific war dead and [[ossuary]] built in May 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spmaguam.org/irei/index.html |script-title=ja:\u5357\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u5354\u4f1a |publisher=South Pacific Memorial Association, Inc}}</ref>\n\n==== New Zealand ====\n* [[Featherston, New Zealand|Featherston]] \u2013 Memorial cenotaph of [[Featherston prisoner of war camp]]\n* [[Christchurch]] - Memorial cenotaph of [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]] people died\n\n==== Northern Mariana Islands ====\n* [[Banzai Cliff]], North end of [[Saipan]] \u2013 {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of war dead in central pacific Ocean''|\u4e2d\u90e8\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Chubu taiheiyou senbotsusha no hi}} for 43,000 Japanese killed in action and 12,000 war dead citizen regardless of nationality including Japanese [[Human migration|migratior]] to [[Battle of Saipan|Saipan]], [[Battle of Tinian|Tinian]], [[Battle of Guam (1941)|Guam]] islands till 1945 war end.(constructed by Japanese government and with cooperation of government of [[Northern Mariana Islands]] in March 1974.)\n\n==== Papua New Guinea ====\n* [[Wewak]] - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of [[New Guinea campaign]] war dead''|\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ae\u30cb\u30a2\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Nyuginia senbotsusya no hi}}, Commemorate and reward for 130,000 Japanese killed in action and 50,000 residents war dead. Constructed by the Japanese government with the cooperation of Papua New Guinea in September 1980. <ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject>>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/seisakunitsuite/bunya/hokabunya/senbotsusha/seido01/index.html |script-title=ja:\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ae\u30cb\u30a2\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|date=2016-01-01|language=Japanese|trans-title=''Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare'', implementation of commemorative project for war dead|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Rabaul]], [[New Britain]], [[Bismarck Archipelago]] -  {{nihongo|'' Cenotaph of Japanese killed in action in [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands|South Pacific Ocean]]''|\u5357\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Minami taiheiyo senbotsusha no hi}}, 200,000 killed in action and war dead in [[Battle of Rabaul (1942)|Battle of Rabaul]] and [[Southeast Area Fleet]]. Constructed by Japanese government and {{nihongo|''Comrades Association in arms''|\u6226\u53cb\u4f1a|Senyukai}} in September 1980.<ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject />\n\n==== [[South West Pacific]] ====\n==== [[Marshall Islands]] ====\n[[Majuro]] - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of war dead in east [[pacific Ocean]]''|\u6771\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Higasi taiheiyou senbotsusha no hi}} (constructed by the Japanese government with the cooperation of the government of Republic of the Marshall Islands in March 1984.)<ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01/ireihi08.html |script-title=ja:\u6771\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891 |quote={{Nihongo2|\u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u653f\u7b56\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 > \u5206\u91ce\u5225\u306e\u653f\u7b56\u4e00\u89a7 > \u4ed6\u5206\u91ce\u306e\u53d6\u308a\u7d44\u307f > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u907a\u65cf\u7b49\u3078\u306e\u63f4\u8b77 > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\u306e\u5b9f\u65bd > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u6771\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891}} |publisher=[[Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare]]}}</ref>\n\n==== [[New Caledonia]] ====\n* [[Thio, New Caledonia|Thio]] - Burial of 230 Japanese people. Immigrants of [[nickel]] mining since 1892.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nichigopress.jp/nichigo_news/goleaks/41243/ |script-title=ja:\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ab\u30ec\u30c9\u30cb\u30a2\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u79fb\u6c11120\u5468\u5e74|date=2012-08-05|language=Japanese|trans-title=120 anniversary of Japanese Immigrants to New Caledonia|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref>\n* Burial, war dead crew of [[Japanese submarine I-17]]<ref>[http://ukikuro.blog84.fc2.com/blog-entry-670.html \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ab\u30ec\u30c9\u30cb\u30a2\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730\u3078]</ref>\n\n==== [[Palau]] ====\n*[[Peleliu]] - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, war dead in west pacific''|\u897f\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Nishi taiheiyou senbutusya no hi}}, built in March 1985.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01/ireihi09.html |script-title=ja:\u897f\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891 |quote={{Nihongo2|\u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u653f\u7b56\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 > \u5206\u91ce\u5225\u306e\u653f\u7b56\u4e00\u89a7 > \u4ed6\u5206\u91ce\u306e\u53d6\u308a\u7d44\u307f > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u907a\u65cf\u7b49\u3078\u306e\u63f4\u8b77 > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\u306e\u5b9f\u65bd > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u897f\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891}} |publisher=[[Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare]]}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Saipan]] ====\n* [[Banzai Cliff]] \u2013 {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, war dead in central pacific''|\u4e2d\u90e8\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Cyubu taiheiyou senbutusya no hi}}, built in March 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01/ireihi03.html |script-title=ja:\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u4e2d\u90e8\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891 |quote={{Nihongo2|\u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u653f\u7b56\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 > \u5206\u91ce\u5225\u306e\u653f\u7b56\u4e00\u89a7 > \u4ed6\u5206\u91ce\u306e\u53d6\u308a\u7d44\u307f > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u907a\u65cf\u7b49\u3078\u306e\u63f4\u8b77 > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\u306e\u5b9f\u65bd}} |publisher=[[Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare]]}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Solomon Islands|Solomon]] ====\n* [[Guadalcanal]] - Solomon peace commemorative park, {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, war dead in Solomon Islands area''|\u30bd\u30ed\u30e2\u30f3\u8af8\u5cf6\u65b9\u9762\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891|Soromon houmen senbutsusha ireihi}} built in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japan-solomon.com/cenotaph/ |script-title=ja:\u6170\u970a\u7891\u7d39\u4ecb |publisher=All Japan Solomon Association}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\n\n==== Canada ====\n* [[Cumberland, British Columbia]] \u2013 Cumberland Japanese cemetery.  Headstones date back to 1901.\n\n==== Dominican Republic ====\n* [[Dajab\u00f3n Province]] \u2013 Cemetery of [[Japanese settlement in the Dominican Republic]].\n\n==== United States ====\n* [[Colma, California]] \u2013 Colma Japanese cemetery, three crew of [[Japanese warship Kanrin Maru]], and others.\n* [[Owens Valley]], [[Inyo County, California|Inyo County]], [[California]] - [[Manzanar]].  Tomb and cenotaph is near to visitor center. The cenotaph was built from a 15 cent donation from each family in the camp in August 1943. It also holds the remains of six people not identified by relatives.\n* [[Queens]], [[New York City]] - Mount Olivet Cemetery. Tomb of  {{Nihongo|Toyohiko Takami|\u9ad8\u898b \u8c4a\u5f66}}, who founded the {{Nihongo|Japanese American Welfare Society|\u7d10\u80b2\u5171\u6e08\u4f1a}} with [[Takamine J\u014dkichi|J\u014dkichi Takamine]] in 1914.\n* [[The Bronx|Bronx]], New York City - [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]]. Tomb of [[Hideyo Noguchi]], [[Takamine J\u014dkichi|J\u014dkichi Takamine]], {{Nihongo|[[Ryoichiro Arai]]|\u65b0\u4e95 \u9818\u4e00\u90ce}} one of the founders of the [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]] and others.\n* [[Brooklyn]], New York City \u2013 [[Cypress Hills National Cemetery]]. Tomb of {{Nihongo|Shido Yamada|\u5c71\u7530 \u5fd7\u9053}}, representative of former [[Sony]], Tokyo Tsushin Kogyo, in New York, and others.\n* [[Makiki]], [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]] \u2013 Makiki Japanese cemetery built in the early 1900s by Japanese immigrants, and the first cemetery of [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] nearby.\n* Honolulu, Hawaii, [[Kakaako Waterfront Park]] - Cenotaph of victims of [[Ehime Maru and USS Greeneville collision]].\n\n=== South America ===\n\n==== Bolivia ====\n* [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz Department]] \u2013 Japanese cemetery in the [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]] public cemetery.\n\n==== Brazil ====\n* [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]] - [[\u00c1lvares Machado]] Japanese cemetery.\n* [[Maraj\u00f3]], [[Par\u00e1]] \u2013 Japanese cemetery. Grave robbed in Jangle.\n* [[Ibirapuera Park]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] \u2013 Cenotaph {{lang|pt|MONUMENTO\u3000EM HOMENAGEM AOS PIONEIROS DA IMIGRA\u00c7\u00c3O JAPONESA FALECIDOS}} ({{Nihongo2|\u30d6\u30e9\u30b8\u30eb\u65e5\u672c\u79fb\u6c11\u958b\u62d3\u5148\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891}})\n\n==== Peru ====\n* [[Ca\u00f1ete Province]], [[Lima Region]] - Casa Blanca Japanese cemetery.\n\n=== Europe ===\n\n==== Malta ====\n* Tomb of war dead of {{Nihongo|[[2nd Special Squadron (Japanese Navy)|2nd Special Squadron]]|\u5927\u65e5\u672c\u5e1d\u56fd\u7b2c\u4e8c\u7279\u52d9\u8266\u968a\u6226\u6b7b\u8005\u4e4b\u5893}} in Kalkara Naval Cemetery. Under [[Anglo-Japanese Alliance]], [[Winston Churchill]] call for [[Squadron (naval)|squadron]] reinforcements to [[Imperial Japanese Navy]], and attacked by [[Torpedo]] from [[German Empire]] [[U-boat]].\n\n==== Russia (Europe region) ====\n*[[Moscow]] - Donskoy Japanese cemetery in [[Donskoy Monastery]]. Tomb of Yasunao Yoshioka ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u5409\u5ca1\u5b89\u76f4|\u5409\u5ca1 \u5b89\u76f4]]}}), [[Harbin]] [[Consul (representative)|Consul]] {{Nihongo|Funao Miyagawa|\u5bae\u5ddd \u8229\u592b}} pass away in [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|prison]] in Moscow in 1950, and others.\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n* [[Wales]] \u2013 Cenotaph of the '''''{{illm|Hirano-maru|ja|\u5e73\u91ce\u4e38}}''''' attacked and [[shipwrecking]] by [[U-boat]] on December 5, 1918. Wooden cenotaph renewed with stone cenotaph on 100th anniversary on  October 4, 2018.<ref>{{cite news| title = Cenotaph Honoring Hirano Maru Sailors Established by UK Volunteer Group\n | url = https://www.nyk.com/english/news/2018/20181005_01.html | agency =[[Nippon Yusen]]\n | accessdate =2019-05-19\n | language =\n | trans_title =\n }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Japan War-Bereaved Families Association]]\n* [[Foreign cemeteries in Japan]]\n* [[Chidorigafuchi National Cemetery]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Japanese diaspora]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries by ethnicity]]\n", "text_old": "{{Grammar|for=grammar|date=February 2020}} \nMany {{nihongo|'''Japanese [[cemeteries]]'''|\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730| Nihonjin bochi}} '''and [[cenotaphs]]''' are located outside of [[Japan]] for [[Japanese people]] who died for various reasons outside the nation of their birth. These reasons include historical circumstances such as war. This article also lists [[tomb]]s and [[Burial ground|burial]] places.\n\n== History ==\nDespite a history of isolationism, many Japanese people have travelled and died outside of Japan. The oldest known [[Japantown]] featuring a Japanese cemetery is in [[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya District|Ayutthaya]], [[Thailand]], which was established in the 14th to 18th century. The oldest known Japanese national recorded by name and buried outside Japan is the early explorer [[Yamada Nagamasa]]. \n\nWars, particularly World War II, accounted for a large portion of Japanese burial places outside Japan. The cemetery of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] in [[Malta]], various burial places of [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|Japanese prisoners of war]] in [[Siberia]], and [[Pacific War]] sites including the [[Nanp\u014d Islands]], [[Philippines|the Philippines]], [[New Guinea]], and other [[Pacific Islands]] feature multiple Japanese cemeteries, cenotaphs, and [[Cadaver|remains]] despite soldiers' organizations and/or Japanese government efforts to recover them.\n\nVictims of the United States' internment of its citizens of Japanese ancestry are prevalent in the western United States. \n\n== Location, name of cemetery, cenotaph and tomb ==\n{{Expand section|date=February 2017}}\n\n=== Asia ===\n\n==== Bhutan ====\n* [[Paro, Bhutan|Paro]] - Burial place with the [[pagoda]] of botanist Keiji Nishioka ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u897f\u5ca1\u4eac\u6cbb|\u897f\u5ca1\u4eac\u6cbb]]}})\n\n==== Cambodia ====\n* [[Phnom Penh]] - Cenotaph, Haruyuki Takada ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u9ad8\u7530\u6674\u884c|\u9ad8\u7530 \u6674\u884c]]}}), police, [[Line of duty death]] participate in [[United Nations Transitional Authority in Cambodia]] \u2013 [[Phnom Penh]]\n* [[Siem Reap Province]] - Tomb, [[Taizo Ichinose]]\n* [[Kampong Thom City]], [[Kampong Thom Province]] - ''Atsu Elementary and junior high school'' and monument ''A'' in a garden bearing the name [[Atsuhito Nakata]]. It was built by his father with donation of Japanese, based on wish of the local people, instead of initial idea of using it for food supply after a flood in 1998.<ref>[https://www.travelbook.co.jp/spot/19062 Atsu Elementary and junior high school, Travel guide]</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n* Hong Kong \u2013 Japanese cemetery, 465 tombs of Japanese who died in Hong Kong in 67 years from 1878 to 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ameblo.jp/ciasia/entry-10080335043.html\n|script-title=ja:\u9999\u6e2f\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730\u6170\u970a\u796d|date=2008-03-16|language =Japanese|trans-title =Hong Kong Japanese cemetery memorial service|access-date=2016-08-26}}</ref>\n* [[Fangzheng County]], [[Heilongjiang]]{{spaced ndash}}[[:zh:\u4e2d\u65e5\u53cb\u597d\u56ed\u6797|Sino-Japanese Friendship Forest]] ({{zh|s=\u4e2d\u65e5\u53cb\u597d\u56ed\u6797}}), originally Fangzheng Japanese Cemetery ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u65b9\u6b63\u5730\u533a\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u516c\u5893}})\n\n* [[Tengchong]], [[Yunnan]] - '''''[[Mountain pass]] of Japanese [[tomb]] ''''' (\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u306e\u5893\u306e\u5ce0), so called by elder people in this area, of killed in action on  '''''[[Battle of Mount Song]]''''' and '''''Battle of Lam\u00e8ng\uff65Tengchong'''''(Japanese [[:ja:\u62c9\u5b5f\u30fb\u9a30\u8d8a\u306e\u6226\u3044]])(Chinese [[:zh:\u9a30\u885d\u6230\u5f79]]) at Lam\u00e8ng (\u62c9\u5b5f), [[Longling County]], [[ Baoshan, Yunnan]] and [[Tengchong]] (\u9a30\u8d8a).<ref>\u4e2d\u56fd\u306b\u6b8b\u308b\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u306e\u907a\u9aa8 \uff62\u30ad\u30e3\u30c3\u30c1! \u4e16\u754c\u306e\u8996\u70b9\uff63 2018\u5e748\u670825\u65e5NHK BS1 \u653e\u9001</ref><ref>[https://4travel.jp/travelogue/10156683 Japanese blog site], back side monumental inscription is \u2018\u2019\u770c\u7d1a\u91cd\u70b9\u6587\u7269\u4fdd\u8b77\u5358\u4f4d\u3000\u6ec7\u897f\u6297\u65e5\u6226\u4e89\u677e\u5c71\u6226\u5f79\u4e3b\u6226\u5834\u907a\u5740\u4e4b\u4e00\u2019\u2019, \u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u6d77\u5916 >\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2 >\u4e2d\u56fd >\u96f2\u5357\u7701 > \u96f2\u5357\u7701 \u65c5\u884c\u8a18 >\u8a73\u7d30, \u96f2\u5357\u7701\u65c5\u884c\u8a18\uff08\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\uff09 \u4e00\u89a7\u306b\u623b\u308b, 2007/05/06 - 2007/05/15, visit battle site in [[Yunnan]] (\u96f2\u5357\u7701\u306e\u6226\u8de1\u3092\u8a2a\u306d\u3066\u30012007 May 9th No. 2)</ref>\n\n==== India ====\n* [[Imphal]] - Cenotaph, the [[Courage|brave]] Japanese who died during war in {{Nihongo|[[Battle of Imphal]]|\u30a4\u30f3\u30d1\u30fc\u30eb\u4f5c\u6226\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u52c7\u58eb\u306e\u7891|Inpaaru sakusen senbotsusha yuushi no hi |lead=yes}})\n* Worli, [[Mumbai]] - Mumbai Japanese cemetery, 3000 Japanese were in Mumbai area to [[Procurement|procure]] cotton in the early of [[Sh\u014dwa period]]. Most of the remains and property of the deceased were brought back to Japan, and the remains of only 30 people remain in Mumbai as of 2008.\n\n==== Indonesia ====\n* [[Jakarta]] - [[Kalibata Heroes Cemetery]], Ex-Japanese soldiers of the [[Pacific War]] who participated in the [[Indonesian National Revolution]]\n* [[Tabanan Regency]] - Cemetery park, Ex-Japanese soldiers of the [[Pacific War]] participated in the [[Indonesian National Revolution]], {{Nihongo|Taman Pujaan Bangsa Margarana|\u30de\u30eb\u30ac\u82f1\u96c4\u5893\u5730\u516c\u5712|Maruga eiyu bochi kouen}})\n\n==== Kazakhstan ====\n* [[Karaganda]] - Burial cenotaph, repose of souls of [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|Japanese prisoners of war]] {{nihongo||\u5e73\u548c\u93ae\u9b42 \u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u57cb\u846c\u7891 Heiwa chinkon Nihonjin maisouhi|}}\n\n==== Laos ====\n* [[Vientiane Province]], [[Nam Ngum Dam]] - The grave site of several Japanese engineers who were surveying possible dam locations who died in December 1960s when their boat overturning. The burial site is in premise of temple close to dam.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.data-max.co.jp/2014/03/24/post_16456_ik1.html |script-title=ja:\u30e9\u30aa\u30b9\u767a\u5c55\u8ca2\u732e\u306e\u77e5\u3089\u308c\u3056\u308b\u65e5\u672c\u4eba|date =2014-03-24|year =|language=Japanese|trans-title =Not widely known Japanese contributed to Laos development|access-date =2016-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Malaysia ====\n* [[Labuan]], [[Borneo]], Labuan Peace Park \u2013 {{nihongo|''Monument of Borneo war dead''|\u30dc\u30eb\u30cd\u30aa\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Chubu taiheiyou senbotsusha no hi}} for 12,000 who died during war in [[Borneo campaign (1945)|Borneo]] and surrounding ocean area. (Constructed by the Japanese government and with the cooperation of government of [[Malaysia]] and the government of [[Sabah]] in September 1982.)<ref name=visitcenotaph >{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon-izokukai.jp/memorial.html |script-title=ja:\u6170\u970a\u7891\u3092\u8a2a\u306d\u308b|date=|language=Japanese|trans-title=Visiting cenotaph|access-date=2016-06-06 }}</ref>\n* [[Kota Kinabalu]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Sandakan]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Tawau]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Kuala Lumpur]] Japanese cemetery. Cenotaph of the people who died on [[Japan Airlines Flight 715]].\n* [[Johor Bahru]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Kuching]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Miri, Malaysia|Miri]] Japanese cemetery (in Tun Datu Tuanku Haji Bujang College)\n* [[Penang]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Ipoh]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Malacca City|Malacca]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Kuala Terengganu]] Japanese cemetery\n\n==== Mongolia ====\nTo resolve the lack of labor power, Mongolian government requested to transfer [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union]] in October and December 1945, Approx 12,318 Japanese prisoners were forced to work, among them more than 1,600 has been died.<ref name=mongol >{{cite web|url=http://web.kyoto-inet.or.jp/people/gyokuju/page013.html |script-title=ja:\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\u6170\u970a\u56e3\u53c2\u7d00\u884c\u8a18|date=|language=Japanese|trans-title=memorial journey in Mongolia|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref> There are 16 Japanese cemeteries including those listed below.\n* Altanbulag [[Selenge Province]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[S\u00fckhbaatar (city)|S\u00fckhbaatar]] Japanese cemetery\n* [[Ulaanbaatar]], {{nihongo|Cenotaph of Japanese|[[:ja:\u30c0\u30f3\u30d0\u30c0\u30eb\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6170\u970a\u7891|\u30c0\u30f3\u30d0\u30c0\u30eb\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6170\u970a\u7891]]|Danbadarujya Nihonjin ireihi}} and {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of Japanese died''|\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6b7b\u4ea1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891|Nihonjin shibousha ireihi}}, for the approximately 1,700 [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|Japanese prisoners]] who died after war ended.(Constructed by Japanese government in October 2001.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01ireihi15.html |script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6b7b\u4ea1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891\uff08\u30e2\u30f3\u30b4\u30eb\uff09|date=\n |language=Japanese|trans-title= Cenotaph of Japanese died (Mongolia)|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref><ref name=mongol />\n* {{Nihongo|''Borujiburan''|\u30db\u30b8\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30f3}} Japanese cemetery<ref name=mongol /> \n* {{Nihongo|''Nanaiha''|\u30ca\u30e9\u30a4\u30cf}} burial (12 Japanese)<ref name=mongol />\n\n==== Myanmar ====\n* [[Yangon]] Japanese cemetery \u2013 For [[Karayuki-san]] and [[Pacific War]] casualties. {{nihongo|''Monument of Peace, [[Burma]]''|\u30d3\u30eb\u30de\u5e73\u548c\u8a18\u5ff5\u7891|Biruma heiwa kinen hi}}, memorial to the approximately 190,000 Japanese were died in war and they pray peace for themselves. (Constructed by the Japanese government in March 1981, then moved and larger in size by the Myanmar government in March 1998.)\n\n==== Nepal ====\n* [[Mustang District]] \u2013 Tomb, with part of ashes, Toru Kondo ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u8fd1\u85e4\u4ea8 (NPO\u7406\u4e8b\u9577)|\u8fd1\u85e4\u4ea8]]}}), contributed development of Mustang District.\n\n==== North Korea ====\nCemetery and burial place of Japanese people lived in the South Korea area before and after [[World War II]]. There are 71 cemeteries and burial places in North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/special/08001/TKY201210010607.html |script-title=ja:\u5e73\u58cc\u90ca\u5916\u306e\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730\u3001\u907a\u65cf\u304c\u521d\u306e\u5893\u53c2\u308a|date=2012-10-01|language=Japanese|trans-title=Bereaved family first visit to Suburb of Pyongyang Japanese cemetery|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Suburb]] of [[Pyongyang]] \u2013 {{Nihongo|Yongsan cemetery|\u9f8d\u5c71\u5893\u5730}}, 2421 people evacuated to Pyongyang after the end of World War II, August 15, 1945, and died in the period of October 1945 to April 1946 due to cold temperature, stagnant and/or illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senbotsusya.com/ryuzan.php|script-title=ja:\u5e73\u58cc\u5e02\u9f8d\u5c71\u5893\u5730\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u57cb\u846c\u8005\u540d\u7c3f|date=2011-08-01|language=Japanese|trans-title=Name list of burial Japanese in Yongsan cemetery, Pyongyang|access-date=2016-09-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227161612/http://www.senbotsusya.com/ryuzan.php|archive-date=2014-02-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Hamhung]] \u2013 Cemetery and burial place.{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n==== Philippines ====\nOne of the bloodiest battlefields of the [[Pacific War]]; there are many cenotaphs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwmemorial.gr.jp/index.htm |script-title=ja:NGO\u30d5\u30a3\u30ea\u30d4\u30f3\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891\u4fdd\u5b58\u5354\u4f1a|date=|language=Japanese|trans-title= Philippines WAR MEMORIAL PRESERVATION ASSOCIATION, INC.|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Luzon]] \u2013 Approximate 270 cenotaph in various locations. [[Kalayaan, Laguna|Kalayaan]] \u2013 {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of war dead in Comrades Association in arms''|\u6bd4\u5cf6\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|fuiripin senbutsusha no hi}}, commemorate approximate 500,000 Japanese war dead in [[Battle of Luzon]]. Constructed by Japanese government in March 1973.<ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject />\n* [[Visayas]] \u2013 Approximate 110 cenotaph in various locations, Japanese war dead of [[Battle of the Visayas]].\n* [[Mindanao]] - Approximate 20 cenotaph in various locations, Japanese war dead of [[Battle of Mindanao]]\n* [[Leyte]] - Cenotaph in [[Tacloban]], [[Ormoc]] and various locations. approximate 80,000 Japanese killed in action out of 520,000 war dead in [[Battle of Leyte]]. {{nihongo|''[[Guanyin]], [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Madonna]] Maria''|\u30de\u30c9\u30f3\u30ca\u30de\u30ea\u30a2\u89b3\u97f3|Madonna Maria Kanon }}, a peace commemoration statue between Asia, including Philippines, and Japan in the Kanfuraw Hill where [[Tacloban]] [[City hall]] is. There is {{Nihongo|Isao Yamazoe|\u5c71\u6dfb\u3000\u52c7\u592b}} Shrine in [[Dulag Airfield]].\n* [[Guiuan, Eastern Samar]], [[Samar]] \u2013 Cenotaph in Dumpao Beach.\n\n==== Russia (Asia region) ====\nAlmost died Japanese is [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union]].\n* [[Primorsky Krai]] \u2013 146 Japanese cemetery or burial place.<ref name=10Jcemetery >{{cite web|url=http://www.vladivostok.ru.emb-japan.go.jp/jap/japan-info/1-primorye-4.html |script-title=ja:\u5728\u30a6\u30e9\u30b8\u30aa\u30b9\u30c8\u30af\u65e5\u672c\u9818\u4e8b\u9928\u3001\uff14\uff0e\u6211\u304c\u56fd\u3068\u306e\u95a2\u4fc2\uff64(8)\u898b\u3069\u3053\u308d,(10)\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730|date=|language=Japanese|trans-title= Consulate-General of Japan in Vladivostok, Relation to Japan,(8) watch spot, (10) Japanese cemetery Japanese|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Norilsk]], [[Krasnoyarsk Krai]] \u2013 Cenotaph of [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|deceased father and others]], constructed by son under the valuable efforts of a student from Russia to Japan, on 2 October 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASHBQ6VJJHBQUTIL070.html |script-title=ja:\u30b7\u30d9\u30ea\u30a2\u6291\u7559\u306e\u5730\u306b\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6170\u970a\u7891\u3000\u30ed\u30b7\u30a2\u4eba\u7559\u5b66\u751f\u304c\u5c3d\u529b |date=2015-11-06\n|language=ja |newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]] |trans-title=Japanese Cenotaph, by the effort of a student from Russia |access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref><ref>[[Yomiuri Shimbun]] 2016-01-10 Ver. 13S Page 37</ref>\n* [[Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk]], [[Sakhalin Oblast]] \u2013 Japanese cemetery, location is from downtown to airport mid-way.<ref name=10Jcemetery />\n* [[Smirnykh]], Sakhalin Oblast - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, [[Sakhalin]]-[[Kuril Islands]] war dead''|\u6a3a\u592a\u30fb\u5343\u5cf6\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891|Karafuto\uff65Chishima Senbotsusha ireihi}} (Constructed by Japanese government in November 1996.<ref name=NihonIzokukai >Home page of [[Japan War-Bereaved Families Association]] in Japanese</ref>\n* Former {{nihongo|''Maokacho''|[[:ja:\u771f\u5ca1\u753a|\u771f\u5ca1\u753a]]| Maokacho}}, [[Kholmsk]], Sakhalin Oblast \u2013 Cenotaph of [[rest in peace]], constructed at a former Japanese cemetery place, by [[Affiliation (family law)|affiliate]] ''Maokacho'' people interested, in August 1995.<ref>[[Yomiuri Shimbun]] 2015-04-24 Ver. 13S Page 7</ref>\n* [[Nagorny (inhabited locality)|Nagornaya]] street, [[Nakhodka]] - Japanese cemetery.<ref name=10Jcemetery /> \n* [[Listvyanka, Irkutsky District, Irkutsk Oblast]], [[Khabarovsk]] \u2013 Japanese cemetery place, {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, Japanese dead''|\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u6b7b\u4ea1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891|Nihonjin shibousha ireihi}} approximate 60,000 and pray eternal peace in [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|Siberia]]. (constructed by the Japanese government July 1995.<ref name=NihonIzokukai />\n* [[Irkutsk Oblast]] \u2013 Cenotaph and approximate 40 buried (including oblast government built 14).<ref name=NihonIzokukai />\n* [[Amur Oblast]] - Cenotaph and approximate 41 buried (including oblast government built 1).<ref name=NihonIzokukai />\n\n==== Singapore ====\n* [[Japanese Cemetery Park]]\n\n==== South Korea ====\n* [[Geumjeong District]], [[Busan|Busan Metropolitan City]] - {{Nihongo|Cenotaph, immigrated Japanese|\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u585a\u79fb\u5b89\u4e4b\u7891|Nihonjin tuka ian no hi}}\n* [[Port Hamilton]] - Japanese cemetery,  removal after [[Treaty of San Francisco]]\n\n==== Taiwan ====\n* [[Tainan]]{{spaced ndash}}{{Nihongo|Houkakuji temple|\u5b9d\u899a\u5bfa}} Japanese [[Cremation|cremated]] [[Cadaver|remains]] [[morgue]]. The former Japanese cemetery ({{zh|t=\u4e09\u677f\u6a4b\u5893\u5730}}) before was [[exhumation]] and displacement took place in 1997. Then tomb of [[Akashi Motojiro]] moved to Cemetery ({{zh|labels=no|c=\u798f\u97f3\u5c71\u57fa\u7763\u6559\u5893\u5730}}) in [[Sanzhi District]], [[Taipei]], other remains moved to Houkakuji temple in [[Taichung]].\n* [[Sanzhi District]], [[Taipei]] \u2013 tomb of [[Akashi Motojiro]]\n* [[Taipei]]{{spaced ndash}}Tomb of ''Teacher Mr. Rokushin'' ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u516d\u6c0f\u5148\u751f|\u516d\u6c0f\u5148\u751f]]}})\n* Taipei - {{Nihongo|Cyuwa zenji|\u4e2d\u548c\u79aa\u5bfa}} Japanese [[Cremation|cremated]] [[Cadaver|remains]] [[morgue]]\n* [[Tainan]]{{spaced ndash}}Tomb of [[Yoichi Hatta]] and his wife.\n* [[Kaohsiung]]{{spaced ndash}}Japanese cemetery in {{ill|Fudingjin|zh|\u8986\u9f0e\u91d1}}\n* [[Hualien County]]{{spaced ndash}}{{Nihongo|Japanese cemetery of ''Houden''\u3000immigration village|\u8c4a\u7530\u79fb\u6c11\u6751\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730}}\n* [[Hualien County]]{{spaced ndash}}{{Nihongo|Konohon company Communal cemetery|\u30b3\u30ce\u30db\u30f3\u793e\u5171\u540c\u5893\u5730}}\n* [[Pingtung County]] {{Nihongo|Cyouonji temple|\u6f6e\u97f3\u5bfa}}{{spaced ndash}}At [[Bashi Channel]], [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] [[destroyer]] ''Kuretake'' ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u5449\u7af9 (\u99c6\u9010\u8266)|\u5449\u7af9]]}}), [[High-speed transport|transport]] ''[[Tamatsu Maru]]'' and many other ships attacked then [[shipwrecking]] by [[United States Navy]] in [[Pacific War]] time. This area was called {{Nihongo|Cemetery of Ships|\u8239\u306e\u5e55\u5834\u306e|Fume no hakaba}} in Japan, more than 100,000 killed in action. Japanese veteran {{Nihongo|Hidetsugu Nakajima|\u4e2d\u5d8b\u79c0\u6b21|extra=died 2013}} survived for 12 days and saved in August 1944. He built \u2019\u2019Cyouonji\u2019\u2019 temple privately at his own cost in 1981 for killed fellow soldier [[memorialization]] and, 60 deceased's family, [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] and Japanese attended menorial ceremony in August 2015.<ref>[[Yomiuri Shimbun]] 2015-Aug.-3 ver. 13S page 4</ref>\n\n==== Tajikistan ====\n* [[Dushanbe]], Tajikistan office of [[United Nations Development Programme]] - Cenotaph, Yutaka Akino ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u79cb\u91ce\u8c4a|\u79cb\u91ce\u8c4a]]}}), voluntary participate from [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)]] staff, dead on duty of [[United Nations Mission of Observers in Tajikistan]].<ref>[[Shinz\u014d Abe]] floral tribute on 2015-10-24, [[Yomiuri Shimbun]] Page 4, 13S edition 2015-10-25</ref>\n\n==== Thailand ====\n\n*[[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya District|Ayutthaya]] - Japanese cemetery is in [[Phra Nakhon Si Ayutthaya District|Ayutthaya]]\n* [[Kanchanaburi]] - {{Nihongo|Cenotaph, Kanchanaburi Memorial Monument|\u30ab\u30f3\u30c1\u30e3\u30ca\u30d6\u30ea\u30fc\u6170\u970a\u5854|Kanchanaburi ireitou}}, Japanese soldiers worked to build [[Mueang Kanchanaburi District]] [[Burma Railway]], including [[prisoner of war]] of [[Allies of World War II]] and workers from the [[Southeast Asia]] region. Built by the Japanese army railway build troops in 1944. [[Epitaph]] is in language with Japanese, English, [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]].\n\n==== Uzbekistan ====\nThere are thirteen Japanese cemeteries in Uzbekistan.<ref>\n{{cite w