ssy]]. Second cenotaph of four Japanese constructed by voluntary war veteran in 1997.\n\n=== Oceania ===\n==== Australia ====\n* [[Broome, Western Australia]] \u2013 Burial of approximately 900 Japanese immigrants in the [[Meiji period]] from [[Taiji, Wakayama]].The immigrants were in Broome to dive for [[pearl]]<nowiki/>s.\n* [[Cowra]] - Cemetery of [[Cowra breakout]] Japanese. \n* [[Darwin, Northern Territory]] \u2013 Cenotaph of [[I-121-class submarine]].<ref>{{cite news\n | title =\u5b89\u500d\u5185\u95a3\u7dcf\u7406\u5927\u81e3\u306b\u3088\u308b\u8c6a\u5dde\u30c0\u30fc\u30a6\u30a3\u30f3\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u4f0a\u53f7\u7b2c124\u6f5c\u6c34\u8266\u6170\u970a\u7891\u8a2a\u554f 2-19-11-17\n | url =https://www.mofa.go.jp/mofaj/a_o/ocn/au/page4_004508.html \n | agency =  [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)]]\n | accessdate =2019-05-19\n | language = Japanese\n | trans_title =\n | quote =[[Prime Minister of Japan]] [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] visit cenotaph of [[I-121-class submarine]] at [[Darwin, Northern Territory]] on 2018 Nov. 17\n }}</ref>  \n* [[Thursday Island, Queensland]] \u2013 Cemetery of Japanese immigrants from the [[Meiji period]] to the end of [[World War II]]. Primary occupation was diving for pearls.\n\n==== [[Guam]] ====\n* ''South Pacific Memorial Park'', Cenotaph of South Pacific war dead and [[ossuary]] built in May 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spmaguam.org/irei/index.html |script-title=ja:\u5357\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u5354\u4f1a |publisher=South Pacific Memorial Association, Inc}}</ref>\n\n==== New Zealand ====\n* [[Featherston, New Zealand|Featherston]] \u2013 Memorial cenotaph of [[Featherston prisoner of war camp]]\n* [[Christchurch]] - Memorial cenotaph of [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]] people died\n\n==== Northern Mariana Islands ====\n* [[Banzai Cliff]], North end of [[Saipan]] \u2013 {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of war dead in central pacific Ocean''|\u4e2d\u90e8\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Chubu taiheiyou senbotsusha no hi}} for 43,000 Japanese killed in action and 12,000 war dead citizen regardless of nationality including Japanese [[Human migration|migratior]] to [[Battle of Saipan|Saipan]], [[Battle of Tinian|Tinian]], [[Battle of Guam (1941)|Guam]] islands till 1945 war end.(constructed by Japanese government and with cooperation of government of [[Northern Mariana Islands]] in March 1974.)\n\n==== Papua New Guinea ====\n* [[Wewak]] - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of [[New Guinea campaign]] war dead''|\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ae\u30cb\u30a2\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Nyuginia senbotsusya no hi}}, Commemorate and reward for 130,000 Japanese killed in action and 50,000 residents war dead. Constructed by the Japanese government with the cooperation of Papua New Guinea in September 1980. <ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject>>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/stf/seisakunitsuite/bunya/hokabunya/senbotsusha/seido01/index.html |script-title=ja:\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ae\u30cb\u30a2\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|date=2016-01-01|language=Japanese|trans-title=''Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare'', implementation of commemorative project for war dead|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Rabaul]], [[New Britain]], [[Bismarck Archipelago]] -  {{nihongo|'' Cenotaph of Japanese killed in action in [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands|South Pacific Ocean]]''|\u5357\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Minami taiheiyo senbotsusha no hi}}, 200,000 killed in action and war dead in [[Battle of Rabaul (1942)|Battle of Rabaul]] and [[Southeast Area Fleet]]. Constructed by Japanese government and {{nihongo|''Comrades Association in arms''|\u6226\u53cb\u4f1a|Senyukai}} in September 1980.<ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject />\n\n==== [[South West Pacific]] ====\n==== [[Marshall Islands]] ====\n[[Majuro]] - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph of war dead in east [[pacific Ocean]]''|\u6771\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Higasi taiheiyou senbotsusha no hi}} (constructed by the Japanese government with the cooperation of the government of Republic of the Marshall Islands in March 1984.)<ref name=MHLWWarDeadProject /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01/ireihi08.html |script-title=ja:\u6771\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891 |quote={{Nihongo2|\u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u653f\u7b56\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 > \u5206\u91ce\u5225\u306e\u653f\u7b56\u4e00\u89a7 > \u4ed6\u5206\u91ce\u306e\u53d6\u308a\u7d44\u307f > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u907a\u65cf\u7b49\u3078\u306e\u63f4\u8b77 > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\u306e\u5b9f\u65bd > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u6771\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891}} |publisher=[[Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare]]}}</ref>\n\n==== [[New Caledonia]] ====\n* [[Thio, New Caledonia|Thio]] - Burial of 230 Japanese people. Immigrants of [[nickel]] mining since 1892.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nichigopress.jp/nichigo_news/goleaks/41243/ |script-title=ja:\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ab\u30ec\u30c9\u30cb\u30a2\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u79fb\u6c11120\u5468\u5e74|date=2012-08-05|language=Japanese|trans-title=120 anniversary of Japanese Immigrants to New Caledonia|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref>\n* Burial, war dead crew of [[Japanese submarine I-17]]<ref>[http://ukikuro.blog84.fc2.com/blog-entry-670.html \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ab\u30ec\u30c9\u30cb\u30a2\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u5893\u5730\u3078]</ref>\n\n==== [[Palau]] ====\n*[[Peleliu]] - {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, war dead in west pacific''|\u897f\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Nishi taiheiyou senbutusya no hi}}, built in March 1985.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01/ireihi09.html |script-title=ja:\u897f\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891 |quote={{Nihongo2|\u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u653f\u7b56\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 > \u5206\u91ce\u5225\u306e\u653f\u7b56\u4e00\u89a7 > \u4ed6\u5206\u91ce\u306e\u53d6\u308a\u7d44\u307f > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u907a\u65cf\u7b49\u3078\u306e\u63f4\u8b77 > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\u306e\u5b9f\u65bd > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u897f\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891}} |publisher=[[Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare]]}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Saipan]] ====\n* [[Banzai Cliff]] \u2013 {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, war dead in central pacific''|\u4e2d\u90e8\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891|Cyubu taiheiyou senbutusya no hi}}, built in March 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhlw.go.jp/bunya/engo/seido01/ireihi03.html |script-title=ja:\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\uff1a\u4e2d\u90e8\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u306e\u7891 |quote={{Nihongo2|\u30db\u30fc\u30e0 > \u653f\u7b56\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 > \u5206\u91ce\u5225\u306e\u653f\u7b56\u4e00\u89a7 > \u4ed6\u5206\u91ce\u306e\u53d6\u308a\u7d44\u307f > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u907a\u65cf\u7b49\u3078\u306e\u63f4\u8b77 > \u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u4e8b\u696d\u306e\u5b9f\u65bd}} |publisher=[[Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare]]}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Solomon Islands|Solomon]] ====\n* [[Guadalcanal]] - Solomon peace commemorative park, {{nihongo|''Cenotaph, war dead in Solomon Islands area''|\u30bd\u30ed\u30e2\u30f3\u8af8\u5cf6\u65b9\u9762\u6226\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891|Soromon houmen senbutsusha ireihi}} built in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japan-solomon.com/cenotaph/ |script-title=ja:\u6170\u970a\u7891\u7d39\u4ecb |publisher=All Japan Solomon Association}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\n\n==== Canada ====\n* [[Cumberland, British Columbia]] \u2013 Cumberland Japanese cemetery.  Headstones date back to 1901.\n\n==== Dominican Republic ====\n* [[Dajab\u00f3n Province]] \u2013 Cemetery of [[Japanese settlement in the Dominican Republic]].\n\n==== United States ====\n* [[Colma, California]] \u2013 Colma Japanese cemetery, three crew of [[Japanese warship Kanrin Maru]], and others.\n* [[Owens Valley]], [[Inyo County, California|Inyo County]], [[California]] - [[Manzanar]].  Tomb and cenotaph is near to visitor center. The cenotaph was built from a 15 cent donation from each family in the camp in August 1943. It also holds the remains of six people not identified by relatives.\n* [[Queens]], [[New York City]] - Mount Olivet Cemetery. Tomb of  {{Nihongo|Toyohiko Takami|\u9ad8\u898b \u8c4a\u5f66}}, who founded the {{Nihongo|Japanese American Welfare Society|\u7d10\u80b2\u5171\u6e08\u4f1a}} with [[Takamine J\u014dkichi|J\u014dkichi Takamine]] in 1914.\n* [[The Bronx|Bronx]], New York City - [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]]. Tomb of [[Hideyo Noguchi]], [[Takamine J\u014dkichi|J\u014dkichi Takamine]], {{Nihongo|[[Ryoichiro Arai]]|\u65b0\u4e95 \u9818\u4e00\u90ce}} one of the founders of the [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]] and others.\n* [[Brooklyn]], New York City \u2013 [[Cypress Hills National Cemetery]]. Tomb of {{Nihongo|Shido Yamada|\u5c71\u7530 \u5fd7\u9053}}, representative of former [[Sony]], Tokyo Tsushin Kogyo, in New York, and others.\n* [[Makiki]], [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]] \u2013 Makiki Japanese cemetery built in the early 1900s by Japanese immigrants, and the first cemetery of [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] nearby.\n* Honolulu, Hawaii, [[Kakaako Waterfront Park]] - Cenotaph of victims of [[Ehime Maru and USS Greeneville collision]].\n\n=== South America ===\n\n==== Bolivia ====\n* [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz Department]] \u2013 Japanese cemetery in the [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]] public cemetery.\n\n==== Brazil ====\n* [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]] - [[\u00c1lvares Machado]] Japanese cemetery.\n* [[Maraj\u00f3]], [[Par\u00e1]] \u2013 Japanese cemetery. Grave robbed in Jangle.\n* [[Ibirapuera Park]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] \u2013 Cenotaph {{lang|pt|MONUMENTO\u3000EM HOMENAGEM AOS PIONEIROS DA IMIGRA\u00c7\u00c3O JAPONESA FALECIDOS}} ({{Nihongo2|\u30d6\u30e9\u30b8\u30eb\u65e5\u672c\u79fb\u6c11\u958b\u62d3\u5148\u6ca1\u8005\u6170\u970a\u7891}})\n\n==== Peru ====\n* [[Ca\u00f1ete Province]], [[Lima Region]] - Casa Blanca Japanese cemetery.\n\n=== Europe ===\n\n==== Malta ====\n* Tomb of war dead of {{Nihongo|[[2nd Special Squadron (Japanese Navy)|2nd Special Squadron]]|\u5927\u65e5\u672c\u5e1d\u56fd\u7b2c\u4e8c\u7279\u52d9\u8266\u968a\u6226\u6b7b\u8005\u4e4b\u5893}} in Kalkara Naval Cemetery. Under [[Anglo-Japanese Alliance]], [[Winston Churchill]] call for [[Squadron (naval)|squadron]] reinforcements to [[Imperial Japanese Navy]], and attacked by [[Torpedo]] from [[German Empire]] [[U-boat]].\n\n==== Russia (Europe region) ====\n*[[Moscow]] - Donskoy Japanese cemetery in [[Donskoy Monastery]]. Tomb of Yasunao Yoshioka ({{Nihongo2|[[:ja:\u5409\u5ca1\u5b89\u76f4|\u5409\u5ca1 \u5b89\u76f4]]}}), [[Harbin]] [[Consul (representative)|Consul]] {{Nihongo|Funao Miyagawa|\u5bae\u5ddd \u8229\u592b}} pass away in [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|prison]] in Moscow in 1950, and others.\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n* [[Wales]] \u2013 Cenotaph of the '''''{{illm|Hirano-maru|ja|\u5e73\u91ce\u4e38}}''''' attacked and [[shipwrecking]] by [[U-boat]] on December 5, 1918. Wooden cenotaph renewed with stone cenotaph on 100th anniversary on  October 4, 2018.<ref>{{cite news| title = Cenotaph Honoring Hirano Maru Sailors Established by UK Volunteer Group\n | url = https://www.nyk.com/english/news/2018/20181005_01.html | agency =[[Nippon Yusen]]\n | accessdate =2019-05-19\n | language =\n | trans_title =\n }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Japan War-Bereaved Families Association]]\n* [[Foreign cemeteries in Japan]]\n* [[Chidorigafuchi National Cemetery]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Japanese diaspora]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries by ethnicity]]\n", "name_user": "CasRose", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed 2 grammar errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_cemeteries_and_cenotaphs"}
{"title_page": "Attabotics", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Robotics company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Attabotics Inc.\n| logo = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_size =\n| former_name = \n| type = [[Privately held company]]\n| owners = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|2016}}\n| founder = Scott Gravelle\n| num_employees = 210\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| hq_location_city = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Canada]]\n| area_served = \n| key_people = Scott Gravelle (CEO, CTO)\n| industry = [[Robotics]] design and manufacturing\n| products = \n| revenue = ~$30 million (2018)<ref name=jsmith/>\n| homepage = {{URL|attabotics.com}}\n}}\n'''Attabotics''' (stylized as ATTAbotics) is a [[Calgary]]-based robotics company which specializes in [[Inventory control|inventory management]] systems. Attabotics was named one of [[CNBC]]'s 100 most promising [[startup]]s in 2019<ref name=sheng>{{Cite web |last=Sheng |first=Ellen |title=Amazon\u2019s ant-size competition in designing the warehouse of the future |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/12/amazons-ant-size-competition-in-creating-warehouse-of-the-future.html |publisher=CNBC |date=2019-11-12 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> and ''[[Fast Company]]''<nowiki />'s 31st most innovative company in 2020.<ref name=fast>{{Cite web |last=Sorokanich |first=Lara |title=The World's 50 Most Innovative Companies: How a nature documentary inspired a cutting-edge design that shrinks massive warehouses into the space of an office building |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90457446/attabotics-most-innovative-companies-2020 |work=Fast Company |date=2020-03-10 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nAttabotics designs and produces a robotic [[inventory]] storage and retrieval system.<ref name=parker/> The Attabotics system uses three dimensions of travel which greatly reduces warehouse [[Floor area|footprint]] and [[Human resources|workforce]] needed compared to a conventional [[fulfillment centre]],<ref name=compelling>{{Cite news |last=Livingstone |first=Barb |title=Compelling Calgarians: Scott Gravelle |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/compelling-calgarians-scott-gravelle/ |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=2020-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107000411/https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/compelling-calgarians-scott-gravelle/ |archivedate=2020-01-07 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> and uses modular [[Container|tote]]s allowing the system to be easily scaled up or down.<ref name=robotreport>{{Cite web |last=Demaitre |first=Eugene |title=Attabotics brings vision of ant-like efficiency to supply chains |url=https://www.therobotreport.com/attabotics-brings-vision-ant-efficiency-supply-chains/ |work=The Robot Report |date=2019-08-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330194411/https://www.therobotreport.com/attabotics-brings-vision-ant-efficiency-supply-chains/ |archivedate=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> [[Nordstrom]]'s [[fulfillment centre]] in [[Newark, California]], which uses Attabotics and [[Tompkins Robotics]] systems, saved 90% floorspace compared to conventional alternatives.<ref name=thomas>{{Cite news |last=Thomas |first=Lauren |title=How Nordstrom uses robots and shelves inspired by ants to deliver lipstick faster |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/05/nordstrom-partners-with-attabotics-and-tompkins-robotics-for-faster-delivery.html |publisher=CNBC |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nAttabotics had a total of $32.7 million in [[Seed funding|funding]] by 2019; investors included [[Coatue Management]], [[Comcast Ventures]], [[Honeywell Ventures]], [[Forerunner Ventures]], and [[Werklund Growth Fund LP]].<ref name=jsmith>{{Cite news |last=Smith |first=Jennifer |title=Logistics Automation Provider Attabotics Raises $25 Million in New Funding  |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/logistics-automation-provider-attabotics-raises-25-million-in-new-funding-11564480801 |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |agency=Reuters |date=2019-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801012614/https://www.wsj.com/articles/logistics-automation-provider-attabotics-raises-25-million-in-new-funding-11564480801 |archivedate=2019-08-01 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> Attabotics has also received government investment from [[Sustainable Development Technology Canada]]<ref name=cleantech>{{Cite web |title=$14.1 M for industrial clean tech investment |url=https://www.ippt.ca/14-1-m-for-industrial-clean-tech-investment/ |work=Industrial Process Products & Technology (IPP&T) |date=2018-04-12 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> and the [[City of Calgary]].<ref name=awarded>{{Cite news |last=Stephenson |first=Amanda |title=Robotic logistics company ATTAbotics awarded $4.5M from city's $100M fund |url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/robotic-logistics-company-attabotics-inc-awarded-4-5m-from-citys-100m-fund/ |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=2018-12-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112123632/https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/robotic-logistics-company-attabotics-inc-awarded-4-5m-from-citys-100m-fund/ |archivedate=2019-11-12 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Attabotics announced a new headquarters building in Northeast Calgary.<ref name=parker>{{Cite news |last=Parker |first=David |title=Parker: ATTAbotics hires local company to design new building |url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/commercial-real-estate/parker-attabotics-hires-local-company-to-design-new-building/ |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=2019-06-17 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> The design, by Calgary-based [[Modern Office of Design + Architecture]], won multiple architectural awards in 2019 and is expected to be complete in 2022.<ref name=moda>{{Cite web |title=Attabotics HQ |url=http://moda.ca/attabotics-hq/ |publisher=Modern Office of Design + Architecture |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330195939/http://moda.ca/attabotics-hq/ |archivedate=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=canarch>{{Cite journal |title=ATTAbotics Headquarters |url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/attabotics-headquarters/ |work=Canadian Architect |volume=64 |number=12 |page=24 |date=December 2019 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=waf>{{Cite web |title=WAF 2019: Day 1 Winners Announced  |url=https://www.archdaily.com/929658/waf-2019-day-1-winners-announced |work=ArchDaily |date=2019-12-04 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> It is designed like a [[wedge]] to conform with nearby [[Calgary Airport]] height restrictions.<ref name=cao>{{Cite web |last=Cao |first=Lilly |title=MoDA's Attabotics Headquarters is Inspired by Ant Colonies |url=https://www.archdaily.com/926001/modas-attabotics-headquarters-is-inspired-by-ant-colonies |work=ArchDaily |date=2019-10-06 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite news |title=Nordstrom partners with tech companies for faster delivery |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rr4WtXooSpo |publisher=CNBC Television |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.attabotics.com Official website]\n\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Calgary]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Robotics company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Attabotics Inc.\n| logo = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_size =\n| former_name = \n| type = [[Privately held company]]\n| owners = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|2016}}\n| founder = Scott Gravelle\n| num_employees = 210\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| hq_location_city = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Canada]]\n| area_served = \n| key_people = Scott Gravelle (CEO, CTO)\n| industry = [[Robotics]] design and manufacturing\n| products = \n| revenue = ~$30 million (2018)<ref name=jsmith/>\n| homepage = {{URL|attabotics.com}}\n}}\n'''Attabotics''' (stylized as ATTAbotics) is a [[Calgary]]-based robotics company which specializes in [[Inventory control|inventory management]] systems. Attabotics was named one of [[CNBC]]'s 100 most promising [[startup]]s in 2019<ref name=sheng>{{Cite web |last=Sheng |first=Ellen |title=Amazon\u2019s ant-size competition in designing the warehouse of the future |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/12/amazons-ant-size-competition-in-creating-warehouse-of-the-future.html |publisher=CNBC |date=2019-11-12 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> and ''[[Fast Company]]''<nowiki />'s 31st most innovative company in 2020.<ref name=fast>{{Cite web |last=Sorokanich |first=Lara |title=The World's 50 Most Innovative Companies: How a nature documentary inspired a cutting-edge design that shrinks massive warehouses into the space of an office building |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90457446/attabotics-most-innovative-companies-2020 |work=Fast Company |date=2020-03-10 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nAttabotics designs and produces a robotic [[inventory]] storage and retrieval system.<ref name=parker/> The Attabotics system uses three dimensions of travel which greatly reduces warehouse [[Floor area|footprint]] and [[Human resources|workforce]] needed compared to a conventional [[fulfillment centre]],<ref name=compelling>{{Cite news |last=Livingstone |first=Barb |title=Compelling Calgarians: Scott Gravelle |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/compelling-calgarians-scott-gravelle/ |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=2020-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107000411/https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/compelling-calgarians-scott-gravelle/ |archivedate=2020-01-07 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> and uses modular [[Container|tote]]s allowing the system to be easily scaled up or down.<ref name=robotreport>{{Cite web |last=Demaitre |first=Eugene |title=Attabotics brings vision of ant-like efficiency to supply chains |url=https://www.therobotreport.com/attabotics-brings-vision-ant-efficiency-supply-chains/ |work=The Robot Report |date=2019-08-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330194411/https://www.therobotreport.com/attabotics-brings-vision-ant-efficiency-supply-chains/ |archivedate=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> [[Nordstrom]]'s [[fulfillment centre]] in [[Newark, California]], which uses Attabotics and [[Tompkins Robotics]] systems, saved 90% floorspace compared to conventional alternatives.<ref name=thomas>{{Cite news |last=Thomas |first=Lauren |title=How Nordstrom uses robots and shelves inspired by ants to deliver lipstick faster |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/05/nordstrom-partners-with-attabotics-and-tompkins-robotics-for-faster-delivery.html |publisher=CNBC |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nAttabotics had a total of $32.7 million in [[Seed funding|funding]] by 2019; investors included [[Coatue Management]], [[Comcast Ventures]], [[Honeywell Ventures]], [[Forerunner Ventures]], and [[Werklund Growth Fund LP]].<ref name=jsmith>{{Cite news |last=Smith |first=Jennifer |title=Logistics Automation Provider Attabotics Raises $25 Million in New Funding  |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/logistics-automation-provider-attabotics-raises-25-million-in-new-funding-11564480801 |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |agency=Reuters |date=2019-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801012614/https://www.wsj.com/articles/logistics-automation-provider-attabotics-raises-25-million-in-new-funding-11564480801 |archivedate=2019-08-01 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> Attabotics has also received government investment from [[Sustainable Development Technology Canada]]<ref name=cleantech>{{Cite web |title=$14.1 M for industrial clean tech investment |url=https://www.ippt.ca/14-1-m-for-industrial-clean-tech-investment/ |work=Industrial Process Products & Technology (IPP&T) |date=2018-04-12 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> and the [[City of Calgary]].<ref name=awarded>{{Cite news |last=Stephenson |first=Amanda |title=Robotic logistics company ATTAbotics awarded $4.5M from city's $100M fund |url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/robotic-logistics-company-attabotics-inc-awarded-4-5m-from-citys-100m-fund/ |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=2018-12-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112123632/https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/robotic-logistics-company-attabotics-inc-awarded-4-5m-from-citys-100m-fund/ |archivedate=2019-11-12 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=dasilva>{{Cite news |last=DaSilva |first=Tomasia |title=Calgary robotic logistics company ATTAbotics Inc. gets $4.5M from city |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4756313/calgary-robotics-company-attabotics-investment/ |publisher=Global News |date=2018-12-12 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Attabotics announced a new headquarters building in Northeast Calgary.<ref name=parker>{{Cite news |last=Parker |first=David |title=Parker: ATTAbotics hires local company to design new building |url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/commercial-real-estate/parker-attabotics-hires-local-company-to-design-new-building/ |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=2019-06-17 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> The design, by Calgary-based [[Modern Office of Design + Architecture]], won multiple architectural awards in 2019 and is expected to be complete in 2022.<ref name=moda>{{Cite web |title=Attabotics HQ |url=http://moda.ca/attabotics-hq/ |publisher=Modern Office of Design + Architecture |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330195939/http://moda.ca/attabotics-hq/ |archivedate=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=canarch>{{Cite journal |title=ATTAbotics Headquarters |url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/attabotics-headquarters/ |work=Canadian Architect |volume=64 |number=12 |page=24 |date=December 2019 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=waf>{{Cite web |title=WAF 2019: Day 1 Winners Announced  |url=https://www.archdaily.com/929658/waf-2019-day-1-winners-announced |work=ArchDaily |date=2019-12-04 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> It is designed like a [[wedge]] to conform with nearby [[Calgary Airport]] height restrictions.<ref name=cao>{{Cite web |last=Cao |first=Lilly |title=MoDA's Attabotics Headquarters is Inspired by Ant Colonies |url=https://www.archdaily.com/926001/modas-attabotics-headquarters-is-inspired-by-ant-colonies |work=ArchDaily |date=2019-10-06 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite news |title=Nordstrom partners with tech companies for faster delivery |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rr4WtXooSpo |publisher=CNBC Television |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.attabotics.com Official website]\n\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Calgary]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2016]]\n", "name_user": "M.nelson", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove duplicate ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attabotics"}
{"title_page": "Hughes Bolckow", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name               = Hughes Bolckow  \n| former_name        = {{Bulleted list|Hughes Bolckow Shipbreaking Company, Ltd|Messrs, Hughes, Bolckow, and Co., Limited}}\n| logo               =  \n| image              =  \n| image_caption      =  \n| type               =  \n| traded_as          =  \n| foundation         =   \n| location_city      = [[Blyth, Northumberland]] \n| location_country   = U.K.\n| locations          =  \n| area_served        =  \n| parent             = [[Metal Industries, Limited|Metal Industries Group subsidiary]] \n| industry           = [[Ship breaking]]  \n| services          = [[Scrap|scrap recycling]]\n}}\n\n'''Hughes Bolckow''' formerly ''Messrs, Hughes, Bolckow, and Co., Limited'' was a well-known shipbreaking company based out of [[Blyth, Northumberland]].\n\n==Background==\n\nIntending to create an industrial park for dismantling obsolete warships in 1911, the company leased {{convert|6|acre|ha}} of land from [[Matthew White Ridley, 3rd Viscount Ridley|Lord Ridley]] and the Blyth Harbour Commissioners.<ref name= \"Mechanical World and Metal Trades Journal p. 131\">{{harvnb|Mechanical World and Metal Trades Journal|1911|p=131}}</ref>\n\nThe company was responsible for scrapping a number of famous Royal Navy ships including [[HMS Prince of Wales (1860)|HMS ''Britannia'' (previously HMS ''Prince of Wales'')]].<ref name= \"The Daily Telegraph p. 11\">{{harvnb|The Daily Telegraph|1915|p=11}}</ref> Their first ship was the former Certified Industrial Training Ship, [[HMS Southampton (1820)|HMS ''Southampton'']], which was sent to [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]] in June 1912 to be broken up.<ref>http://www.northeastmaritime.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=10764#p21102</ref> In response to requests from customers, the company created a series of \"choice Antiques\" from the fine old seasoned timber they possessed from ''Britannia.''<ref name= \"Studio International Art p. v\">{{harvnb|Studio International Art|1918|p=v}}</ref> The company even had a Ship Timber Department that would create articles manufactured from teakwood taken from obsolete battleships and preserved in \"Solignum.\"<ref name= \"The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser p. 613\">{{harvnb|The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser|1913|p=613}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]] Messrs, Hughes, Bolckow, and Co., Limited experimented with employing women in jobs that were traditionally reserved for men.<ref name= \"Woollacott p. 31-32\">{{harvnb|Woollacott|1994|pp=31\u201332}}</ref> By 1916 13% of the workforce were women; the UK [[Ministry of Labour (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Labour]] approved the work provided the women did not have to lift a sledgehammer weighing more than {{convert|5|lbs|kg}}.<ref name= \"Woollacott p. 31-32\"/>\n\nIn 1921 the company acquired four huge concrete hangars at the [[Marske-by-the-Sea]] Aerodrome in North Yorkshire. The hangars also had an attached {{convert|30|acres|ha}} of land that the company announced would be used to store and to dispose of material purchased by the company from dumps in France.<ref name= \"Spooner p. 68\">{{harvnb|Spooner|1921|p=68}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of its existence the company bought up a number of other companies such as the ''Worth, Mackenzie ft Company'', Limited, which was purchased in 1935.<ref name= \"Institute of Cast Metals Engineers p. 116\">{{harvnb|Institute of British Foundrymen, Welsh Engineers' and Founders' Association|Foundry Trades' Equipment & Supplies Association|1935|p=116}}</ref> By 1952 it had become a subsidiary of [[Metal Industries, Limited]] and was listed on their books.<ref name= \"The Times p. 7\">{{harvnb|The Times|1952|p=7}}</ref> In 1960 The Hughes Bolchow Shipbreaking Co., Ltd., of Blyth changed its name to Hughes Bolckow Ltd. so as to serve notice that although its main activity was still in shipbreaking, the company was branching out.<ref name= \"Shipping World p. \">{{harvnb|Shipping World|1960|p=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Blyth Shipbuilding Company]]\n  \n==Bibliography== \n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|20em}}\n'''References '''\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Institute of British Foundrymen, Welsh Engineers' and Founders' Association|last2=Foundry Trades' Equipment & Supplies Association|authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1935|title=Hughes Bolckow|trans_title= |journal= [[Institute of Cast Metals Engineers|The Foundry Trade Journal]]|volume=  52|issue= |pages= |id= |quote=|publisher=[[Institute of Cast Metals Engineers]] |issn=}}\n*{{cite news |ref=harv|last=The Daily Telegraph|authorlink=The Daily Telegraph |title= H.M.S. Britannia &ndash; The Passing of an Historic Ship|first=  |author2= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/ww1-archive/11411711/Daily-Telegraph-February-15-1915.html |newspaper= The Daily Telegraph|publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=15 February 1915|page= |pages= |at= |accessdate= 16 February 2015 |language= |quote= |archiveurl=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/ww1-archive/11411711/Daily-Telegraph-February-15-1915.html |archivedate=16 February 2015 }}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Mechanical World and Metal Trades Journal|first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1911|title=Mechanical World|trans_title= |journal= Mechanical World and Metal Trades Journal|volume=  50|issue= |pages= |id= |quote=|publisher= |issn=}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Shipping World|first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1960|title=Shipping World|trans_title= |journal= Shipping World|volume=  142|issue=  |pages= |id= |quote=|publisher= |issn=}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Spooner|first= Stanley |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=January 1921 |title=Marske by the sea Aerodrome Acquired|trans_title= |journal= Flight &ndash; The Aircraft Engineer & Airships|volume= No. 631  |issue= 4, Vol. XIII |pages= |id= |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1921/1921%20-%200068.html|accessdate= 16 February 2015 |quote=|publisher=[[Royal Aero Club|Royal Aero Club of The United Kingdom]] |issn=0015-3710}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Studio International Art|first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1918|title=Antiques|trans_title= |journal= Studio International Art|volume=  75&ndash;76|issue= |pages= |id= |quote=|publisher=[[Nat Mags|National Magazine Company]] |issn=}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv|last=Woollacott|first=Angela | authorlink = | title = On Her Their Lives Depend: Munitions Workers in the Great War|url=https://archive.org/details/onhertheirlivesd0000wool|url-access=registration|year=1994| publisher = [[University of California Press]]| isbn= 9780520914650}} <small>- Total pages: 241 </small>\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser|first=|authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1913|title=The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser|trans_title= |journal= The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser|volume=  74|issue= 1936-1948 |pages= |id= |quote=|publisher=W. Rider & son |issn=}}\n*{{cite news |ref=harv|title= The Times|first= |last=The Times|authorlink=The Times |author2= |url= |format= |newspaper=The Times |publisher= |location=London, UK |isbn= |issn=0140-0460|oclc= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=4 September 1952|page= |pages= |at= |language= |quote= |archiveurl= |archivedate= }}\n\n[[Category:Defunct shipbuilding companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ship breaking]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Blyth, Northumberland]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name               = Hughes Bolckow  \n| former_name        = {{Bulleted list|Hughes Bolckow Shipbreaking Company, Ltd|Messrs, Hughes, Bolckow, and Co., Limited}}\n| logo               =  \n| image              =  \n| image_caption      =  \n| type               =  \n| traded_as          =  \n| foundation         =   \n| location_city      = [[Blyth, Northumberland]] \n| location_country   = U.K.\n| locations          =  \n| area_served        =  \n| parent             = [[Metal Industries, Limited|Metal Industries Group subsidiary]] \n| industry           = [[Ship breaking]]  \n| services          = [[Scrap|scrap recycling]]\n}}\n\n'''Hughes Bolckow''' formerly ''Messrs, Hughes, Bolckow, and Co., Limited'' was a well-known shipbreaking company based out of [[Blyth, Northumberland]].\n\n==Background==\n\nIntending to create an industrial park for dismantling obsolete warships in 1911, the company leased {{convert|6|acre|ha}} of land from [[Matthew White Ridley, 3rd Viscount Ridley|Lord Ridley]] and the Blyth Harbour Commissioners.<ref name= \"Mechanical World and Metal Trades Journal p. 131\">{{harvnb|Mechanical World and Metal Trades Journal|1911|p=131}}</ref>\n\nThe company was responsible for scrapping a number of famous Royal Navy ships including [[HMS Prince of Wales (1860)|HMS ''Britannia'']].<ref name= \"The Daily Telegraph p. 11\">{{harvnb|The Daily Telegraph|1915|p=11}}</ref>  Their first ship was the former Certified Industrial Training Ship, [[HMS Southampton (1820)|HMS ''Southampton'']], which was sent to [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]] in June 1912 to be broken up<ref>http://www.northeastmaritime.co.uk/viewtopic.php?t=10764#p21102</ref>. `In response to requests from customers, the company created a series of \"choice Antiques\" from the fine old seasoned timber they possessed from the old [[HMS Prince of Wales (1860)|HMS ''Britannia'' (previously HMS ''Prince of Wales'')]].<ref name= \"Studio International Art p. v\">{{harvnb|Studio International Art|1918|p=v}}</ref> The company even had a Ship Timber Department that would create articles manufactured from teakwood taken from obsolete battleships and preserved in \"Solignum.\"<ref name= \"The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser p. 613\">{{harvnb|The Timber Trades Journal and Saw-mill Advertiser|1913|p=613}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]] Messrs, Hughes, Bolckow, and Co., Limited experimented with employing women in jobs that were traditionally reserved for men.<ref name= \"Woollacott p. 31-32\">{{harvnb|Woollacott|1994|pp=31\u201332}}</ref> By 1916 13% of the workforce were women; the UK [[Ministry of Labour (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Labour]] approved the work provided the women did not have to lift a sledgehammer weighing more than {{convert|5|lbs|kg}}.<ref name= \"Woollacott p. 31-32\"/>\n\nIn 1921 the company acquired four huge concrete hangars at the [[Marske-by-the-Sea]] Aerodrome in North Yorkshire. The hangars also had an attached {{convert|30|acres|ha}} of land that the company announced would be used to store and to dispose of material purchased by the company from dumps in France.<ref name= \"Spooner p. 68\">{{harvnb|Spooner|1921|p=68}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of its existence the company bought up a number of other companies such as the ''Worth, Mackenzie ft Company'', Limited, which was purchased in 1935.<ref name= \"Institute of Cast Metals Engineers p. 116\">{{harvnb|Institute of British Foundrymen, Welsh Engineers' and Founders' Association|Foundry Trades' Equipment & Supplies Association|1935|p=116}}</ref> By 1952 it had become a subsidiary of [[Metal Industries, Limited]] and was listed on their books.<ref name= \"The Times p. 7\">{{harvnb|The Times|1952|p=7}}</ref> In 1960 The Hughes Bolchow Shipbreaking Co., Ltd., of Blyth changed its name to Hughes Bolckow Ltd. so as to serve notice that although its main activity was still in shipbreaking, the company was branching out.<ref name= \"Shipping World p. \">{{harvnb|Shipping World|1960|p=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Blyth Shipbuilding Company]]\n  \n==Bibliography== \n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|20em}}\n'''References '''\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv|last=Institute of British Foundrymen, Welsh Engineers' and Founders' Association|last2=Foundry Trades' Equipment & Supplies Association|authorli